{"title_page": "Cheomseongdae", "text_new": "{{other uses|Kaesong Chomsongdae}}\n{{short description|Astronomical observatory in Gyeongju, South Korea}}\n{{coord|35|50|05.0|N|129|13|08.4|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|img=Korea-Gyeongju-Cheomseongdae-02.jpg\n|hangul=\ucca8\uc131\ub300\n|hanja=\u77bb\u661f\u81fa\n|rr=Cheomseongdae\n|mr=Ch'\u014fms\u014fngdae\n}}\n'''Cheomseongdae''' ([[Hangul]]: \ucca8\uc131\ub300) is an [[astronomical observatory]] in [[Gyeongju]], [[South Korea]]. Cheomseongdae means ''star-gazing tower'' in [[Korean language|Korean]].  Cheomseongdae is the oldest surviving astronomical observatory in Asia,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Storey|first1=Glenn|title=Urbanism in the Preindustrial World: Cross-Cultural Approaches|publisher=[[University of Alabama Press]]|isbn=9780817352462|page=201|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P43ChiFyVVEC&pg=PA201#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2006-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Dicati|first1=Renato|title=Stamping Through Astronomy|publisher=[[Springer Science & Business Media]]|isbn=9788847028296|page=30|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XaBEAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2013-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Bernardi|first1=Gabriella|title=The Unforgotten Sisters: Female Astronomers and Scientists before Caroline Herschel|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319261270|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G-a9CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA40#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2016-03-14}}</ref> and possibly even the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kelley|first1=David H.|last2=Milone|first2=Eugene F.|title=Exploring Ancient Skies: A Survey of Ancient and Cultural Astronomy|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9781441976246|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILBuYcGASxcC&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2011-02-16}}</ref><ref name=ewha>{{cite book|last1=Park|first1=Chang-bom|title=Astronomy: Traditional Korean Science|publisher=Ewha Womans University Press|isbn=9788973007790|page=63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbmOuw2Rh14C&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Selin|first1=Helaine|title=Encyclopaedia of the History of Science, Technology, and Medicine in Non-Westen Cultures|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9789401714167|page=503|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GzjpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA503#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>  It was constructed in the 7th century in the kingdom of [[Silla]], whose capital was Seorabeol, or present-day Gyeongju ([[Hangul]]: \uacbd\uc8fc). Cheomseongdae was designated as the country's [[national treasures of Korea|31st national treasure]] on December 20, 1962.<ref>Indiana University Resources [http://www.indiana.edu/~easc/resources/korea_slides/science/9-1.htm].  Retrieved February 13th, 2006.</ref> Modeled on [[Baekje]]'s ''Jeomseongdae'', which now exists only in historical records, the ''Cheomseongdae'' influenced the construction of a Japanese observatory in 675, and Duke Zhou's observatory in China in 723.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Park|first1=Changbom|title=Astronomy: Traditional Korean Science|publisher=Ewha Womans University Press|isbn=9788973007790|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbmOuw2Rh14C&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=24 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAccording to ''[[Samguk sagi]]'', Cheomseongdae was constructed under the reign of [[Queen Seondeok of Silla|Queen Seondeok]] (632-647) near the capital of the kingdom.  ''Cheomseongdae'' means \"star gazing platform\".\n\nThe construction of the building lasted five years owing to its complexity.\n\n==Structure==\n\nCheomseongdae stands 9.17 meters high and consists of three parts: a [[stylobate]], or base upon which a [[column]] is constructed, a curved cylindrical body, and a square top. Midway up the body stands a square window and entrance to the inside of the structure. When viewed from above, Cheomseongdae resembles the Korean [[Hanja]] character [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BA%95  \u4e95] (Hangul: \uc815 \"jeong\"), meaning \"well.\" <ref name=study>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.astronomicalheritage.net/images/astronomicalheritage.net/media/ahp_entities/entity000019/ch05cs4.pdf|title=Case Study 5.4: Cheomseongdae Observatory, Republic of Korea|last=Park|first=Jeong Eun|website=UNESCO Portal to the Heritage of Astronomy}}</ref>\n\nThe square stylobate base is 5.7 meters wide and built from a single layer of 12 rectangular stones.<ref name=study/><ref name=ewha/> From the base to the window, the tower is filled with earth and rubble.<ref name=study/>\n\nThe cylindrical body of the tower is built out of 365 pieces of cut [[granite]], symbolizing the number of days in a [[year]].<ref name=study/> However, various historical documents have reported different numbers of stones. Song (1983) cites a 1962 survey of the site by Gyeongju National Museum director Hong Sa-jun, who found 366 blocks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Song|first=Sang-Yong|date=1983|title=A brief history of the study of the Ch'\u014fms\u014fng-dae in Kyongju|url=http://www.ekoreajournal.net/search/result.htm?s_Idx_books=264&authorName=&Title=&keywords=&types=&subject=&sYY=0&eYY=0#|journal=Korea Journal|volume=23|issue=8|pages=16\u201321|via=eKorea Journal}}</ref> This discrepancy in stone count may be attributed to some researchers including or omitting a stone slab inside the top of the tower and not visible from the outside.<ref name=ewha/> The stones are fashioned as [[Annulus (mathematics)|annular sectors]], meaning each stone takes the shape of a curved or bent rectangle.\n\nIts construction style parallels that used at the [[Bunhwangsa|Bunhwangsa Temple]] in Gyeongju.\n\n==Symbolism==\n\nThe number and placement of the stones in Cheomseongdae have been theorized to represent various historical and astronomical figures.\n\nThe central hole or window separates the body into 12 layers of stones both above and below, symbolizing the 12 months in a year and the 24 [[solar term]]s.<ref name=study/> Additionally, the 12 stones which comprise the stylobate may also reference the 12 months.<ref name=ewha/>\n\n[[File:CheomseongdaeModel2.jpg|thumb|150px|A scaled down model of Cheomseongdae showing its use as an observatory]]\n\n==Preservation==\nCheomseongdae's original appearance and shape has remained unchanged for over 1300 years; however the structure now tilts slightly to the north-east.<ref name=UNESCO/> In 2007, a system was installed to measure the state of Cheomseongdae every hour. Of particular concern are cracks and structural displacements, and movements of the foundation stones. Cheomseongdae is additionally susceptible to wear due to aging and weathering, particularly from air pollution and structural imbalance caused by [[Subsidence|ground subsidence]]. The exterior of the structure is regularly washed down to remove moss.<ref name=UNESCO>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.astronomicalheritage.net/index.php/show-entity?identity=19&idsubentity=1|title=UNESCO Astronomy and World Heritage Webportal - Show entity|website=www3.astronomicalheritage.net|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>\n\nThe National Research Institute of Cultural Heritage in Korea has conducted inspections on the structure regularly since 1981. The Gyeongju municipal government oversees the site's management and preservation.<ref name=UNESCO/>\n\n==Popular culture==\nCheomseongdae is mentioned in the popular [[Korean drama]] ''[[Queen Seondeok (TV series)|Queen Seondeok]]''. In the 2009 drama, Cheomseongdae was constructed when Queen Seondeok was still a princess; this was her first decree as a princess. Cheomseongdae was meant to share the knowledge of astronomy with everyone, rather than letting one person (Lady [[Misil]]) abuse the knowledge of it. By doing so, she also abdicated her divine rights. Because this was uncommon at the time and unsupported by many conservatives, at the opening of Cheomseongdae, barely any nobles showed up.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\">\n1930 Cheomseongdae, Gyeongju.jpeg|Historic photograph from 1930\nFile:\uc6b0\uc911\ucca8\uc131\ub300.jpg|A rainy view\n\ucca8\uc131\ub300 \uc57c\uacbd.jpg|A night view\nCheomseongdae Night Violet.jpg|Illuminated in violet\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*Jeon, Sang-woon.  (1998). ''A history of science in Korea''.  Seoul:Jimoondang.  {{ISBN|89-88095-11-1}}\n* [http://www.ekoreajournal.net/search/result.htm?s_Idx_books=395&authorName=&Title=&keywords=&types=&subject=&sYY=0&eYY=0# Nha, Il-seong. Silla's Cheomseongdae. (2001) ''Korea Journal'' 41(4), 269-281 (2001)]\n* [http://www.ekoreajournal.net/search/result.htm?s_Idx_books=264&authorName=&Title=&keywords=&types=&subject=&sYY=0&eYY=0# Song, Sang-Yong. ''A brief history of the study of the Ch'\u014fms\u014fng-dae in Kyongju''; ''Korea Journal'' 23(8), 16-21 (1983)]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[https://www3.astronomicalheritage.net/index.php/show-entity?identity=19&idsubentity=1 UNESCO Portal to the Heritage of Astronomy - Cheomseongdae]\n*[http://www.orientalarchitecture.com/koreasouth/gyeongju/cheomseongdae.php Asian Historical Architecture: Cheomseongdae]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060222141500/http://www.lifeinkorea.com/Travel2/kyongju/193 Travel in Korea Cheomsongdae information page]\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 7th century]]\n[[Category:Towers]]\n[[Category:National Treasures of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Korea]]\n[[Category:Silla]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in North Gyeongsang Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Kaesong Chomsongdae}}\n{{short description|Astronomical observatory in Gyeongju, South Korea}}\n{{coord|35|50|05.0|N|129|13|08.4|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|img=Korea-Gyeongju-Cheomseongdae-02.jpg\n|hangul=\ucca8\uc131\ub300\n|hanja=\u77bb\u661f\u81fa\n|rr=Cheomseongdae\n|mr=Ch'\u014fms\u014fngdae\n}}\n'''Cheomseongdae''' ([[Hangul]]: \ucca8\uc131\ub300) is an [[astronomical observatory]] in [[Gyeongju]], [[South Korea]]. Cheomseongdae means ''star-gazing tower'' in [[Korean language|Korean]].  Cheomseongdae is the oldest surviving astronomical observatory in Asia,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Storey|first1=Glenn|title=Urbanism in the Preindustrial World: Cross-Cultural Approaches|publisher=[[University of Alabama Press]]|isbn=9780817352462|page=201|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P43ChiFyVVEC&pg=PA201#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2006-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Dicati|first1=Renato|title=Stamping Through Astronomy|publisher=[[Springer Science & Business Media]]|isbn=9788847028296|page=30|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XaBEAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2013-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Bernardi|first1=Gabriella|title=The Unforgotten Sisters: Female Astronomers and Scientists before Caroline Herschel|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319261270|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G-a9CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA40#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2016-03-14}}</ref> and possibly even the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kelley|first1=David H.|last2=Milone|first2=Eugene F.|title=Exploring Ancient Skies: A Survey of Ancient and Cultural Astronomy|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9781441976246|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILBuYcGASxcC&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en|date=2011-02-16}}</ref><ref name=ewha>{{cite book|last1=Park|first1=Chang-bom|title=Astronomy: Traditional Korean Science|publisher=Ewha Womans University Press|isbn=9788973007790|page=63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbmOuw2Rh14C&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Selin|first1=Helaine|title=Encyclopaedia of the History of Science, Technology, and Medicine in Non-Westen Cultures|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9789401714167|page=503|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GzjpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA503#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>  It was constructed in the 7th century in the kingdom of [[Silla]], whose capital was Seorabeol, or present-day Gyeongju ([[Hangul]]: \uacbd\uc8fc). Cheomseongdae was designated as the country's [[national treasures of Korea|31st national treasure]] on December 20, 1962.<ref>Indiana University Resources [http://www.indiana.edu/~easc/resources/korea_slides/science/9-1.htm].  Retrieved February 13th, 2006.</ref> Modeled on [[Baekje]]'s ''Jeomseongdae'', which now exists only in historical records, the ''Cheomseongdae'' influenced the construction of a Japanese observatory in 675, and Duke Zhou's observatory in China in 723.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Park|first1=Changbom|title=Astronomy: Traditional Korean Science|publisher=Ewha Womans University Press|isbn=9788973007790|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbmOuw2Rh14C&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=24 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAccording to ''[[Samguk sagi]]'', Cheomseongdae was constructed under the reign of [[Queen Seondeok of Silla|Queen Seondeok]] (632-647) near the capital of the kingdom.  ''Cheomseongdae'' means \"star gazing platform\".\n\nThe Construction of the building lasted 5 years due to it's complexity.\n\n==Structure==\n\nCheomseongdae stands 9.17 meters high and consists of three parts: a [[stylobate]], or base upon which a [[column]] is constructed, a curved cylindrical body, and a square top. Midway up the body stands a square window and entrance to the inside of the structure. When viewed from above, Cheomseongdae resembles the Korean [[Hanja]] character [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BA%95  \u4e95] (Hangul: \uc815 \"jeong\"), meaning \"well.\" <ref name=study>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.astronomicalheritage.net/images/astronomicalheritage.net/media/ahp_entities/entity000019/ch05cs4.pdf|title=Case Study 5.4: Cheomseongdae Observatory, Republic of Korea|last=Park|first=Jeong Eun|website=UNESCO Portal to the Heritage of Astronomy}}</ref>\n\nThe square stylobate base is 5.7 meters wide and built from a single layer of 12 rectangular stones.<ref name=study/><ref name=ewha/> From the base to the window, the tower is filled with earth and rubble.<ref name=study/>\n\nThe cylindrical body of the tower is built out of 365 pieces of cut [[granite]], symbolizing the number of days in a [[year]].<ref name=study/> However, various historical documents have reported different numbers of stones. Song (1983) cites a 1962 survey of the site by Gyeongju National Museum director Hong Sa-jun, who found 366 blocks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Song|first=Sang-Yong|date=1983|title=A brief history of the study of the Ch'\u014fms\u014fng-dae in Kyongju|url=http://www.ekoreajournal.net/search/result.htm?s_Idx_books=264&authorName=&Title=&keywords=&types=&subject=&sYY=0&eYY=0#|journal=Korea Journal|volume=23|issue=8|pages=16\u201321|via=eKorea Journal}}</ref> This discrepancy in stone count may be attributed to some researchers including or omitting a stone slab inside the top of the tower and not visible from the outside.<ref name=ewha/> The stones are fashioned as [[Annulus (mathematics)|annular sectors]], meaning each stone takes the shape of a curved or bent rectangle.\n\nIts construction style parallels that used at the [[Bunhwangsa|Bunhwangsa Temple]] in Gyeongju.\n\n==Symbolism==\n\nThe number and placement of the stones in Cheomseongdae have been theorized to represent various historical and astronomical figures.\n\nThe central hole or window separates the body into 12 layers of stones both above and below, symbolizing the 12 months in a year and the 24 [[solar term]]s.<ref name=study/> Additionally, the 12 stones which comprise the stylobate may also reference the 12 months.<ref name=ewha/>\n\n[[File:CheomseongdaeModel2.jpg|thumb|150px|A scaled down model of Cheomseongdae showing its use as an observatory]]\n\n==Preservation==\nCheomseongdae's original appearance and shape has remained unchanged for over 1300 years; however the structure now tilts slightly to the north-east.<ref name=UNESCO/> In 2007, a system was installed to measure the state of Cheomseongdae every hour. Of particular concern are cracks and structural displacements, and movements of the foundation stones. Cheomseongdae is additionally susceptible to wear due to aging and weathering, particularly from air pollution and structural imbalance caused by [[Subsidence|ground subsidence]]. The exterior of the structure is regularly washed down to remove moss.<ref name=UNESCO>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.astronomicalheritage.net/index.php/show-entity?identity=19&idsubentity=1|title=UNESCO Astronomy and World Heritage Webportal - Show entity|website=www3.astronomicalheritage.net|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>\n\nThe National Research Institute of Cultural Heritage in Korea has conducted inspections on the structure regularly since 1981. The Gyeongju municipal government oversees the site's management and preservation.<ref name=UNESCO/>\n\n==Popular culture==\nCheomseongdae is mentioned in the popular [[Korean drama]] ''[[Queen Seondeok (TV series)|Queen Seondeok]]''. In the 2009 drama, Cheomseongdae was constructed when Queen Seondeok was still a princess; this was her first decree as a princess. Cheomseongdae was meant to share the knowledge of astronomy with everyone, rather than letting one person (Lady [[Misil]]) abuse the knowledge of it. By doing so, she also abdicated her divine rights. Because this was uncommon at the time and unsupported by many conservatives, at the opening of Cheomseongdae, barely any nobles showed up.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\">\n1930 Cheomseongdae, Gyeongju.jpeg|Historic photograph from 1930\nFile:\uc6b0\uc911\ucca8\uc131\ub300.jpg|A rainy view\n\ucca8\uc131\ub300 \uc57c\uacbd.jpg|A night view\nCheomseongdae Night Violet.jpg|Illuminated in violet\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*Jeon, Sang-woon.  (1998). ''A history of science in Korea''.  Seoul:Jimoondang.  {{ISBN|89-88095-11-1}}\n* [http://www.ekoreajournal.net/search/result.htm?s_Idx_books=395&authorName=&Title=&keywords=&types=&subject=&sYY=0&eYY=0# Nha, Il-seong. Silla's Cheomseongdae. (2001) ''Korea Journal'' 41(4), 269-281 (2001)]\n* [http://www.ekoreajournal.net/search/result.htm?s_Idx_books=264&authorName=&Title=&keywords=&types=&subject=&sYY=0&eYY=0# Song, Sang-Yong. ''A brief history of the study of the Ch'\u014fms\u014fng-dae in Kyongju''; ''Korea Journal'' 23(8), 16-21 (1983)]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[https://www3.astronomicalheritage.net/index.php/show-entity?identity=19&idsubentity=1 UNESCO Portal to the Heritage of Astronomy - Cheomseongdae]\n*[http://www.orientalarchitecture.com/koreasouth/gyeongju/cheomseongdae.php Asian Historical Architecture: Cheomseongdae]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060222141500/http://www.lifeinkorea.com/Travel2/kyongju/193 Travel in Korea Cheomsongdae information page]\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 7th century]]\n[[Category:Towers]]\n[[Category:National Treasures of South Korea]]\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Korea]]\n[[Category:Silla]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in North Gyeongsang Province]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheomseongdae"}
{"title_page": "United States military beret flash", "text_new": "{{multiple image\n|header   = How beret flashes are worn in the US military\n|perrow   = 1/2/1/1\n|width1   = 320\n|image1   = Seven Green berets.jpg\n|caption1 = US Army special forces soldiers from the seven special forces groups, denoted by the different beret flashes underneath the [[United States Army Special Forces#Distinctive Unit Insignia|1st Special Forces distinctive unit insignia]]\n|width2   = 150\n|image2   = COL Herman Johnson official portrait.jpg\n|caption2 = A US Army officer wearing 82nd Sustainment Brigade beret flash with rank insignia on top of flash\n|width3   = 166\n|image3   = US Air Force Combat Aviation Advisors wearing brown beret.jpg\n|caption3 = A US Air Force NCO (L) and officer (R) wearing CAA beret flash; officer wearing rank insignia on top of flash\n|width4   = 320\n|image4   = USAF 17th STS ceremony-cropped.jpg\n|caption4 = A US Air Force officer wearing Special Tactics Officer beret flash with miniature rank insignia below it (L) next to an NCO wearing the TACP beret flash and crest (R)\n|width5   = 320\n|image5   = Multinational Force and Observers host ANZAC Day 151426-A-BE343-001.jpg\n|caption5 = A [[Canadian Army]] [[Major general#Canada|general officer]] and his US Army [[senior enlisted advisor]] wearing Multinational Force and Observers beret flashes, one metal (L) and one cloth (R)\n}}\nIn the [[United States]] (US) [[United States Armed Forces|armed forces]], a '''beret flash''' is a shield-shaped embroidered cloth or metallic insignia that is usually attached to a stiffener backing of a [[Military beret#United States|military beret]].  Today, the attached flash is worn over the left eye of the wearer with the excess cloth of the beret folded and pulled over the right ear giving it a distinctive shape.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\">[https://armypubs.army.mil/ProductMaps/PubForm/Details.aspx?PUB_ID=1002149 Department of the Army Pamphlet 670\u20131, Uniform and Insignia Guide to the Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia], armypubs.army.mil, dated 25 May 2017, last accessed 4 July 2017</ref><ref name=\"AFI36-2903\">[http://static.e-publishing.af.mil/production/1/af_a1/publication/afi36-2903/afi36-2903.pdf Air Force Instruction 36-2903, Dress and Personal Appearance of Air Force Personnel], Department of the Air Force, Air Force e-Publishing, dated 7 February 2020, updated 18 March 2020, last accessed 25 March 2020</ref>  The embroidered designs of the [[United States Army|US Army's]] [[Berets of the United States Army|beret]] flashes represent the distinctive heraldic colors and patterns of a special mission unit or represent the US Army overall<ref name=\"TIOH\">[https://tioh.army.mil/Catalog/HeraldryList.aspx?CategoryId=11&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services US Army / US Army Heraldry / Beret Flash and Background Trimmings], The Institute of Heraldry, last accessed 12 February 2020</ref> while the [[United States Air Force|US Air Force]]'s represent their [[Air Force Specialty Code]] (AFSC) or their assignment to a special unit.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/>  Joint beret flashes, such as the [[Multinational Force and Observers]] and [[United Nations peacekeeping|United Nations Peacekeepers]] beret flashes, are worn by all of the US armed forces on unique berets while assigned to a specific multinational mission.<ref name=\"Observers\">[https://www.army.mil/article/167541/war_eagle_troopers_receive_multinational_force_and_observers_medal War Eagle Troopers receive Multinational Force and Observers medal], Army.mil, by MAJ Michael Soyka and SGT William A. Tanner, dated 9 May 2016, last accessed 28 April 2018</ref><ref name=\"UN Beret\">[https://www.army.mil/article/111873/army_contributions_to_un_liberia_mission_significant_former_force_chief_says Army contributions to U.N. Liberia mission significant, former force chief says], Army.mil, by Lisa A. Ferdinando, dated 20 September 2013, last accessed 28 April 2018</ref>\n\nWith the exception of Joint beret flashes and other unique conditions, US Army [[soldier]]s and [[non-commissioned officer]]s (NCOs) attach their [[distinctive unit insignia]] (DUI) to the beret's flash.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/>  US Army [[Warrant officer (United States)|Warrant officers]] and [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned officers]] attach their polished metal [[United States Army officer rank insignia|rank insignia]] to their beret flash while chaplains attach their polished metal [[United States Army branch insignia|branch insignia]].<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/>  US Air Force commissioned officers in the [[United States Air Force Security Forces|Security Forces]] or assigned to Combat Aviation Advisor (CAA) [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]]s wear their beret flash in the same manner as the US Army.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"USAF Advisors\">[http://www.afsoc.af.mil/News/Article-Display/article/1410562/quiet-professionals-don-brown-beret/ Quiet Professionals don brown beret], US Air Force Special Operations Command, by Capt Monique Roux, dated 8 January 2018, last accessed 28 April 2018</ref>  Other US Air Force commissioned officers in the [[United States Air Force Tactical Air Control Party|Tactical Air Control Party]] (TACP) AFSC and those authorized large metallic beret flashes attach a miniature version of their polished metal [[United States Air Force officer rank insignia|rank insignia]] below their beret flash or crest.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/>  US Air Force [[airman]] and NCOs only wear their large metallic beret flash, cloth beret flash, or cloth beret flash with crest on AFSC or unit specific berets.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"USAF Advisors\"/>\n\n==History==\n===US Army===\nThroughout its history, US Army soldiers and their units have adopted different [[headgear]] and headgear devices\u2014such as [[Uniforms of the United States Army|color accoutrements]], [[Distinctive unit insignia|insignias]], and flashes\u2014signifying special capabilities and unique roles of soldiers and their units.<ref name=\"Colorful History\">[https://connectingvets.radio.com/articles/news/controversial-history-us-army-and-berets The colorful and controversial history of the Army's berets], ConnectingVets.Radio.com, by Jack Murphy, dated 23 October 2019, last accessed 18 January 2020</ref><ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\">[http://cgsc.cdmhost.com/cdm/ref/collection/p4013coll9/id/602 AR 670-1 1981 (OBSOLETE) : Wear and appearance of Army uniforms and insignia], Department of the Army via Ike Skelton Combined Arms Research Library Digital Library, dated 1 November 1981, last accessed 26 March 2019</ref>  An example of this are organizational beret flashes worn to signify a specific formation of a specialized unit, such as a [[Security Force Assistance Brigade|combat advisor]], [[Airborne forces|airborne]], [[United States Army Rangers|ranger]], or [[Special Forces (United States Army)|special forces]] unit.<ref name=\"TIOH\"/><ref name=\"Colorful History\"/><ref name=\"Army Beret\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180704012922/http://www.armyreal.com/resources/item/1927 History of the Army Beret, CSA SENDS - THE ARMY BLACK BERET], armyreal.com, last accessed 12 February 2020</ref>\n\n[[File:US Army Special Forces UDT training-1956.png|thumb|325px|Special forces soldiers wearing their Parachutist Badge as the beret's flash\u2014note the two officers wearing their polished metal rank insignia below their badge\u2014ca. 1956]]\n{{Stack|{{multiple image\n|direction= vertical\n|align    = right\n|width    = 105\n|image1   = US Army Airborne basic parachutist badge.gif\n|caption1 = Basic Parachutist Badge\n|image2   = US Army Airborne senior parachutist badge.gif\n|caption2 = Senior Parachutist Badge\n}}}}\nIt is not clear when organizational beret flashes began to be used by the US Army.  However, US Army films and photographs between 1956 and 1962 suggest these beret flashes may have been introduced in late 1961,<ref name=\"SF UDT Training 1956\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Jmq1nCtgBA&t=791s Special Forces UDT Training at Okinawa & Army Mules ~ 1956 US Army; The Big Picture TV-372], the US Army's \"The Big Picture,\" Pictorial Report No. 29; from Jeff Quitney YouTube Channel, published 3 March 2017, last accessed 19 June 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7AFG2uqkFnE&t=445s Army Special Forces: \"Silent Warriors\" US Army 1961; The Big Picture TV-518], the US Army's \"The Big Picture;\" from Jeff Quitney YouTube Channel, published 22 October 2014; last accessed 19 June 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DHX1Aww7B0A Green Berets: \"Special Forces\" 1962 US Army; Henry Fonda; The Big Picture TV-547], the US Army's \"The Big Picture;\" from Jeff Quitney YouTube Channel, published 19 November 2015; last accessed 19 June 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/24197082/chester-victor-clifton MG Chester Victor Clifton, Jr], Find a Grave, Memorials, dated 26 Jan 2008, last accessed 4 April 2019</ref> around the time the [[green beret]] was officially authorized for wear by members of the US Army Special Forces.<ref name=\"Beret History\">[https://www.thebalancecareers.com/u-s-military-beret-history-3331980 The Beret in U.S. Military Uniform History], The Balance Careers, by Rod Powers,  updated 27 June 2019, last accessed 14 September 2019</ref><ref name=\"www.army.mil\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20010624053826/https://www.army.mil/features/beret/beret.htm#History A Short History of the Use of Berets in the U.S. Army], army.mil via WebArchive, dated 03 November 2000, last accessed 26 March 2019</ref>  Prior to that time, the green beret was worn informally by special forces soldiers who used their [[Parachutist Badge (United States)|Parachutist Badge]] as their beret flash.  The Parachutist Badge was worn high on the beret positioned either over the left eye or left temple and officers would wear their polished metal rank insignia below their badge.<ref name=\"SF UDT Training 1956\"/>\n\nOther beret accouterments began to appear between 1973 and 1979 when the [[United States Department of the Army|US Department of the Army]]'s morale-enhancing order was in force and various colored berets began to be worn my numerous units and [[United States Army branch insignia|branches of the US Army]].<ref name=\"Beret History\"/><ref name=\"www.army.mil\"/><ref name=\"armystudyguide\">[https://www.armystudyguide.com/content/army_board_study_guide_topics/uniforms/history-of-the-beret.shtml Army Study Guide, History of the Beret], ArmyStudyGuide.com, last accessed 26 March 2019</ref><ref name=\"Various Army Berets\">[http://www.usmilitariaforum.com/forums/index.php?/topic/7676-us-army-berets-blue-black-green-maroon-tan/ US Army berets - blue, black, green, maroon, tan...], The US Militaria Forum, last accessed 23 March 2020</ref>  In 1973, the [[82nd Airborne Division]] (ABN Div) began wearing [[maroon beret]]s and in 1974 the [[101st Airborne Division|101st ABN Div]] began wearing dark-blue berets.<ref name=\"82nd Podcast 25\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gOZGkh_621o All American Legacy Podcast Ep 25 - The French Hat], 82nd Airborne Division Official YouTube Channel, dated 26 June 2017, last accessed 24 March 2020</ref>  Historical photographs of 82nd ABN Div [[paratrooper]]s show them wearing either their Parachutist Badge on their beret\u2014just as the Special Forces had done in the 1950s<ref name=\"SF UDT Training 1956\"/>\u2014as well as their unit specific [[Parachutist Badge (United States)#Airborne background trimming|background trimming]]<ref name=\"TIOH\"/>\u2014which made their debut in [[World War II]]<ref name=\"Trimming\">[http://www.angelfire.com/md2/patches/other/airborne2.html Insignia of Airborne Units, U.S. Army, Second World War, Airborne Breast Oval Background Trimmings], American Military Patches, Other Insignia and Decorations of World War Two, by Dr. Howard G. Lanham, dated 2001, last accessed 24 June 2017</ref>\u2014with officers wearing their polished metal rank insignia below it or they wore their unit's DUI as the beret's flash.<ref name=\"MAJ McKinney\">[https://helenair.com/news/local/stories-of-honor-dan-mckinney-follows-in-father-s-footsteps/article_26e65dc1-97b7-5f0a-a110-a320c40f6cdd.html Stories of Honor: Dan McKinney follows in father's footsteps with Vietnam service, From the Stories of Honor: Honoring Helena-area veterans across generations series], [[Independent Record]], bt Curt Synness, dated 22 July 2019, lasted accessed 30 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"82nd Soldier 1973\">[https://archives.hunaheritage.org/digital-heritage/robert-wolfe-served-us-army-82nd-airborne1st-ranger-battalion Robert Wolfe served in the U.S. Army, 82nd Airborne/1st Ranger Battalion], archives.hunaheritage.org, dated 28 February 1973, last accessed 24 March 2020</ref>  Similarly, historical photographs of 101st ABN Div soldiers show them wearing traditionally styled US Army organizational beret flashes pattered after their unit's [[Air Assault Badge#Background trimmings|background trimming]] with their polished metal rank insignia (enlisted, NCOs, and officers alike) on top and their [[Air Assault Badge]]\u2014if qualified\u2014to the soldier's left-side of the beret flash.<ref name=\"82nd Podcast 25\"/><ref name=\"101st Blue Berets\">[https://www.facebook.com/82ndAirborneDivision/posts/10158970798165387 On episode 25 of the All American Legacy Podcast, we mention the blue beret of the 101st Airborne Division in the 1970s. Well, here is the proof.], 82nd Airborne Division official Facebook page, dated 28 June 2017, last accessed 23 March 2020</ref>  Another example is the [[List of U.S. Army armored cavalry regiments|US Army's armored cavalry regiments]] in [[Germany]] who began wearing [[black beret]]s with maroon and white cloth ovals behind their DUIs, to the left of the wearer's polished metal rank insignia (enlisted, NCOs, and officers alike), over their left temple.<ref name=\"Beret History\"/><ref name=\"www.army.mil\"/><ref name=\"armystudyguide\"/><ref name=\"Cavalry Oval\">[http://www.usmilitariaforum.com/forums/index.php?/topic/211572-military-oval-or-not/ Military Oval or not?], U.S. Militaria Forum, last accessed 28 April 2018</ref>  Also during this time, the [[172nd Infantry Brigade (United States)|172nd Infantry Brigade]] began to wear olive-brown berets with traditionally styled organizational beret flashes with each battalion having their own unique but related designs and was worn in the same manner as today's organizational beret flashes.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/><ref name=\"www.army.mil\"/><ref name=\"Various Army Berets\"/>  By 1979, the US Army put a stop to the use of berets by conventional forces, leaving only special forces and ranger units the authority to wear berets.<ref name=\"Beret History\"/><ref name=\"www.army.mil\"/><ref name=\"armystudyguide\"/>\n{|align=center\n|{{multiple image\n|direction= vertical\n|width    = 150\n|image1   = US Army 2nd Inf Bde-82nd ABN Div-Trimming.png\n|caption1 = 325th Infantry Regiment Background Trimming, ca. World War II\u20132006<ref name=\"2nd INF BDE WW2\">[https://www.historicalimagebank.com/gallery/v/album02/album35/album99/W2Au39d-+Ike+jacket+worn+by+a+sergeant+of+325th+Glider+Infantry-82nd+Airborne+Division.html W2Au39d-Ike jacket worn by a sergeant of 325th Glider Infantry-82nd Airborne Division], Military and Historical Image Bank, last accessed 12 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"TIOH 2nd IBCT\">[https://tioh.army.mil/Catalog/HeraldryMulti.aspx?CategoryId=4865&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services 2nd Brigade Combat Team 82nd Airborne Divison, Beret Flash, Background Trimming], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, dated 8 March 2006, last accessed 12 April 2020</ref>\n|image2   = Dan McKinney-SonTay Raider-1946-2017.jpg\n|caption2 = An officer with the 82nd ABN Div wearing his Parachutist Badge with 325th Infantry Regiment Background Trimming above his rank insignia as the beret's flash, ca. 1970s\n}}\n|{{multiple image\n|direction= vertical\n|width1   = 110\n|image1   = 782nd BrigSupBn.gif\n|caption1 = 1958\u20131994: 782nd Maintenance Battalion DUI<ref name=\"782nd DUI\">[https://tioh.army.mil/Catalog/HeraldryMulti.aspx?CategoryId=4594&grp=2&menu=Uniformed%20Services 782nd Support Battalion Distinctive Unit Insignia], U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry, dated 31 January 2007, last accessed 3 April 2020</ref>\n|width2   = 130\n|image2   = Robert Wolfe-782nd Maintenance BN-82nd DIV Support CMD-1973.png\n|caption2 = A paratrooper with the 82nd ABN Div wearing 782nd Maintenance Battalion DUI as the beret's flash, ca. 1973\n}}\n|{{multiple image\n|direction= vertical\n|width    = 150\n|image1   = US Army 326th Bde Eng Bn Trimming.svg\n|caption1 = [[326th Engineer Battalion (United States)|326th Engineer Battalion (Eng BN)]] Background Trimming, ca. World War II\n|image2   = US Army 326th Brigade Engineering Battalion carimony-circa 1970s.png\n|caption2 = An officer with the 101st ABN Div wearing 326th Eng BN Beret Flash\u2014note its similarity to the unit's background trimming\u2014with his rank insignia on top adjacent to his Air Assault Badge, ca. 1970s\n}}\n|{{multiple image\n|align    = right\n|direction= vertical\n|width1   = 105\n|image1   = US Army historical armored cavalry regiment beret flash.svg\n|caption1 =  Cavalry Oval Beret Flash, ca. 1970s\n|width2   = 140\n|image2   = US Army historical 11th Armored Cavalry Regiment black beret-circa 1973-1979.jpg\n|caption2 = A senior NCO wearing Cavalry Oval Beret Flash with [[11th Armored Cavalry Regiment]] DUI attached, adjacent to his rank insignia, ca. 1970s\n}}\n|}\n\n[[File:SP4 Keith Campbell-11th SFG-KIA 1967.jpg|thumb|130px|A special operations soldier wearing 1st Special Forces DUI above the 11th SFG(A) Recognition Bar as the beret's flash, ca. 1967]]\n{{Stack|{{multiple image\n|direction= vertical\n|align    = right\n|width    = 100\n|image1   = 11thSFG Flash.png\n|caption1 = 11th Special Forces Group (SFG) (Airborne) organizational beret flash\n|image2   = US Army 11th SFG Recognition Bar.svg\n|caption2 = 11th SFG(A) recognition bar\n}}}}\nIn 1980 the US Army reversed part of its decision allowing airborne units to wear maroon berets, ranger units black berets\u2014which switched to [[tan beret]]s in 2001\u2014and special forces units green berets.<ref name=\"Army Beret\"/><ref name=\"Beret History\"/><ref name=\"www.army.mil\"/><ref name=\"armystudyguide\"/>  The US Army's 1981 uniform regulation describes the wear of these newly approved berets with the only authorized accoutrements being officer rank insignias, DUIs, recognition bars, and organizational beret flashes; however, organizational beret flashes were only worn by select units and soldiers.<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/><ref name=\"Recognition Bar\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=pLPvCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT65&dq=us+army+recognition+bar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfjNzc8KfhAhWiuVkKHQzlDgIQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=us%20army%20recognition%20bar&f=false US Army Special Forces 1952\u201384], Bloomsbury Publishing, by Gordon L. Rottman, dated 20 September 2012, {{ISBN|9781782004462}}, last accessed 29 March 2019</ref>  For example, only special operations qualified soldiers were authorized to wear their special forces unit's organizational beret flash while none-qualified soldiers wore a cloth recognition bar\u2014color and pattern matched to their unit's organizational beret flash\u2014below their DUI or officer rank insignia.<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/><ref name=\"Recognition Bar\"/>  The recognition bar was discontinued in 1984 when the [[Special Forces Tab]] was authorized and all soldiers assigned to a special forces unit were required to wear their unit's organizational beret flash.<ref name=\"Recognition Bar\"/>  Throughout the 1980s, organizational beret flashes started to become the norm for all units authorized to wear berets.<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/><ref name=\"Recognition Bar\"/><ref name=\"82nd ABN Urgent Fury\">[http://www.pbase.com/olyinaz/urgent_fury_grenada Operation Urgent Fury (Grenada) (US Military photo gallery)], PBase.com, by Oly Olson, last accessed 4 July 2018</ref>\n\nThe design of each unit's organizational beret flash was created and/or approved by the [[United States Army Institute of Heraldry|US Army Institute of Heraldry]] (TIOH).<ref name=\"AR670-1\">[https://armypubs.army.mil/ProductMaps/PubForm/Details.aspx?PUB_ID=1001129 Army Regulation 670\u20131, Uniform and Insignia Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia], Department of the Army, armypubs.army.mil, dated 25 May 2017, last accessed 4 July 2017</ref> TIOH based their design of each organizational beret flash after a unit's background trimming<ref name=\"TIOH\"/> or [[:File:United States Army Institute of Heraldry.ogv|TIOH research into a unit]]\u2019s [[heraldry]].\n\nIn late 2000, when [[General (United States)|General]] [[Eric Shinseki]], [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Chief of Staff of the Army]], decided to make the black beret the standard headgear of the US Army, he also decided that all units that did not have an organizational beret flash will wear a new universal one.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/><ref name=\"Army Beret\"/><ref name=\"AR670-1\"/>  However, units can request authorization for an organizational beret flash,<ref name=\"Heraldic Orders\">[https://www.heraldry.army.mil/ Clothing and Heraldry PSID], US Army TACOM Life Cycle Management Command, last accessed 8 September 2019</ref> as was done for the US Army's new Security Force Assistance Command and its brigades for wear on their brown berets.<ref name=\"TIOH SFAC\">[https://www.rmda.army.mil/readingroom/'/ReadingRoom/FileDownload.dl?docId=a10396fa-4eb6-4d15-b68a-b83153dd0caa' Authorized Insignia for the Security Force Assistance Command]; Department of the Army, The Institute of Heraldry; AAMH-IHS; dated 16 November 2018; last accessed 14 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"TIOH 1st SFAB Flash\">[https://www.rmda.army.mil/readingroom/'/ReadingRoom/FileDownload.dl?docId=e49abba8-84dd-483e-b176-6199495ad183' Beret Flash for the 1st Security Force Assistance Brigade]; Department of the Army, The Institute of Heraldry; AAMH-IHS; dated 9 February 2018; last accessed 14 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"TIOH 2nd SFAB Flash\">[https://www.rmda.army.mil/readingroom/'/ReadingRoom/FileDownload.dl?docId=bd8d9756-c101-4ace-bfbd-af73e9c138e8' Beret Flash for the 2d Security Force Assistance Brigade]; Department of the Army, The Institute of Heraldry; AAMH-IHS; dated 7 June 2018; last accessed 14 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"TIOH 3rd SFAB Flash\">[https://www.rmda.army.mil/readingroom/'/ReadingRoom/FileDownload.dl?docId=564c0016-0686-4458-9eeb-75b29e468688' Beret Flash for the 3d Security Force Assistance Brigade]; Department of the Army, The Institute of Heraldry; AAMH-IHS; dated 8 August 2018; last accessed 14 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"TIOH 4th SFAB\">[https://www.rmda.army.mil/readingroom/'/ReadingRoom/FileDownload.dl?docId=a5a44fa2-fc8e-4e0e-a40c-7e858f03cb60' Authorized Insignia for the 4th Security Force Assistance Brigade]; Department of the Army, The Institute of Heraldry; AAMH-IHS; dated 8 January 2019; last accessed 14 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"TIOH 5th SFAB\">[https://www.rmda.army.mil/readingroom/'/ReadingRoom/FileDownload.dl?docId=f6ba0915-39a7-4e5d-9ed7-828424a570ae' Authorized Insignia for the 5th Security Force Assistance Brigade]; Department of the Army, The Institute of Heraldry; SAAA-IHS; dated 31 July 2019; last accessed 14 April 2020</ref>  According to Pam Reece of TIOH, the universal US Army Beret Flash \"is designed to closely replicate the colors of the [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the [[Continental Army]] at the time of its [[Siege of Yorktown|victory at Yorktown]].\"<ref name=\"Army Beret\"/>\n\n===US Air Force===\nIn 1957, the [[Strategic Air Command Elite Guard|Strategic Air Command's Elite Guard]] was the first US Air Force unit authorized to wear berets.  The first beret flash worn on the unit's navy-blue beret was a metal full-color replica of the [[:File:SAC Shield.svg|Strategic Air Command Shield]].<ref name=\"Book\">[https://books.google.com/books/about/Defensor_Fortis.html?id=j5_vS-ltlFIC&hl=en Defensor Fortis: A Brief History of USAF Security And Those Dedicated Few Who Defend The Air Force At The Ground Level (pages 37\u201338)], Universal Publishers Press, by Kali Pinckney, dated 1 November 2003, last accessed 5 July 2018</ref><ref name=\"SAC Guard\">[http://www.saceliteguard.com/Elite%20Guard%20History.html SAC Elite Guard History, The Real History of the Air Force Blue Beret], by Col Ray Balcer (USAF), dated April 2005, last accessed 5 July 2018</ref>  In 1966/67, the newly formed [[Phu Cat Air Base Security Forces|1041st Security Police Squadron]] was authorized to wear a different shade of dark-blue beret and used a depiction of a [[falcon]] on a light-blue cloth patch as their beret flash until the unit was disbanded in 1968.<ref name=\"beret\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094744/https://www.safesideassociation.org/blue_beret.html History of the Security Police Beret], by Safeside Association, last accessed 5 July 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.usmilitariaforum.com/forums/index.php?/topic/28664-usaf-security-police-squadrons-in-vietnam/ USAF Security Police Squadrons in Vietnam], usmilitariaforum.com, posted 22 March 2009, last accessed 14 July 2017</ref>  In February 1976, the US Air Force approved the navy-blue beret, worn by Strategic Air Command's Elite Guard and US Air Force Combat Controllers, as the official uniform item for all US Air Force police and security forces.<ref name=\"beret\"/><ref name=\"CCT History\">[https://media.defense.gov/2018/Mar/01/2001885059/-1/-1/0/B_0149_MARION_BROTHERS_IN_BERETS.PDF Brothers in Berets, The Evolution of Air Force Special Tactics, 1953-2003]; [[Air University Press]], Curtis E. LeMay Center for Doctrine Development and Education, [[Maxwell Air Force Base]], Air Force History and Museums Program, in conjunction with Air Force Special Operations Command; by Forrest L. Marion, PhD; dated January 2018; last accessed 1 April 2020</ref>  The beret flash used on these berets was a metal full-color replica of the police or security forces' [[List of Major Commands of the United States Air Force|major command shield]].  In early 1997, the US Air Force stood up the Security Forces AFSC and honored the heraldry of the 1041st Security Police Squadron by creating a new cloth beret flash for all Security Forces airman and NCOs that depict the 1041st's falcon over an airfield with the motto \"Defensor Fortis\" (defenders of the force) embroidered on a scroll at its base; officers wear a similar beret flash\u2014minus the depiction of a falcon and airfield\u2014and wear their metal rank insignia centered on this flash.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"beret\"/>\n{|align=center\n|{{multiple image\n|width1  = 140\n|image1  = US Air Force 1041st SPS beret flash-Historical.png\n|caption1= 1041st Security Police Squadron's Beret Flash\n|width2  = 240\n|image2  = US Air Force 1041sr SPS airman conducting pistol practice-1967.jpg\n|caption2= A Security Policeman with the 1041st Security Police Squadron wearing the unit's distinctive beret and flash, ca. 1968\n}}\n|{{multiple image\n|width1  = 110\n|image1  = ACC Shield.svg\n|caption1= ACC Shield, a major command of the US Air Force\n|width2  = 150\n|image2  = US Air Force Security Policeman A1C Krawchenko-1990.jpg\n|caption2= A Security Policeman wearing the ACC Shield as the beret's flash, ca. 1990\n}}\n|}\n\n{{Annotated image\n| image = US Air Force Combat Controllers at Tachikawa Air Base\u2013Japan-1964.png\n| image-width = 205\n| image-left = -10\n| image-top = -5\n| width = 190\n| height = 195\n| float = right\n| annotations =\n| caption = A CCT NCO wearing his Senior Parachutist Badge and metal rank insignia over his right temple as the beret's flash, ca. 1964\n}}\nHistorical photographs from 1964 on\u2014during the [[Vietnam Era]]\u2014show [[United States Air Force Combat Control Team|US Air Force Combat Controllers]] (CCTs) wearing navy\u2013blue berets.<ref name=\"CCT Japan\">[http://www.sgtmacsbar.com/CCTPhotos/Gallery07/Japan/Japan.html SgtMacsBar\u2013CCT in Japan], sgtmacsbar.com, last accessed 31 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"Vietnam CCT\">[http://www.sgtmacsbar.com/CCTersRemembered/CCTersRemembered.html This Gallery Is To Inform You Of The Most Recent Passing Of Those Within Our Brotherhood, I'm So Sorry!; MKP Air Base Thailand, May 1967], sgtmacsbar.com, last accessed 17 July 2017</ref>  Initial wear of these berets followed the trend of the US Army Special Forces whereby Combat Controller's wore their Parachutist Badge over their left eye acting as the beret's flash with officers wearing their metal rank insignia below their badge; yet other CCTs wore these berets with their Parachutists Badge and metal rank insignia (enlisted, NCO, and officer alike) over their right temple with the excess of the beret's material pulled over the left hear.<ref name=\"SF UDT Training 1956\"/><ref name=\"CSAR 1967\"/><ref name=\"CCT Japan\"/><ref name=\"Vietnam CCT\"/>  In May 1978, the CCTs switched to wearing [[Red beret|scarlet berets]] as well as a unique large metallic Combat Controller Beret Flash, created by retired CCTs Jack Hughes and Gene Adcock.<ref name=\"CCT History\"/>  The new scarlet beret and beret flash were worn in the same manner as it is today, centered over the left eye with officers\u2014known as [[United States Air Force Special Tactics Officer|Special Tactics Officer]]s\u2014wearing their miniature polished metal rank insignia just below a modified version of this large metallic beret flash.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"CCT History\"/><ref name=\"CCT Memorial\">[http://www.cctmemorial.com/Brothers/F/Fagan_G/Memory.html Combat Control Memorial, Remembering Our Fallen Brothers], cctmemorial.com, last accessed 6 April 2019</ref><ref name=\"STO and CRO\">[https://www.airforce.com/api/document/download/1455&ved=2ahUKEwj4qPaT7dHoAhUEqJ4KHSyZD6oQFjACegQIARAB&usg=AOvVaw2dLs1ykUge2zslecY3nqLw&cshid=1586109294133S Special Tactics Officer and Combat Rescue Officer Application\u2013FY2020] US Air Force, last accessed 5 April 2020</ref>\n\n[[File:USAF A1C Roger Klenovich-circa 1967.jpg|thumb|left|170px|A Pararescuemen wearing his Parachutist Badge as the beret's flash, ca. 1967]] \nIn early 1966, US Air Force [[United States Air Force Pararescue|Pararescuemen]] started wearing the maroon beret.<ref name=\"CSAR 1967\">[http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/Visit/Museum-Exhibits/Fact-Sheets/Display/Article/195919/combat-search-and-rescue-in-southeast-asia/ Combat Search and Rescue in Southeast Asia], National Museum of the US Air Force, dated 18 May 2015, last accessed 17 July 2017</ref>  Initial wear of these berets followed the trend of the era whereby Pararescuemen used their Parachutist Badge, worn over the left eye, as the beret's flash.<ref name=\"SF UDT Training 1956\"/><ref name=\"CSAR 1967\"/>  Historical photographs from the Fall 1975 graduating class of Pararescuemen show the graduates wearing the modern-day large metallic Pararescueman Beret Flash on their newly earned berets and worn in the same manner as before.<ref name=\"1975 Para Graduation\">[http://airman.dodlive.mil/2013/12/jump-man/ JUMP MAN, Oldest active-duty airman jumps from Vietnam era to present day], airman.dodlive.mil, dated 23 December 2013, last accessed 17 July 2017</ref>  These Pararescueman Beret Flashes consist of a [[guardian angel]] wrapping its arms around the Earth\u2014which symbolizes the mission of Pararescuemen\u2014surrounded by a parachute mounted on a banner with the phrase, \"That others may live,\" embossed at its base\u2014the pararescue creed.<ref name=\"PJ Flash\">[https://www.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/116336/pararescuemen-honoring-fallen-warriors/ Pararescuemen: Honoring fallen warriors], af.mil, by SSgt Mareshah Haynes ([[Defense Media Activity]]), dated 22 June 2010, last accessed 2 April 2020</ref>  Officers\u2014known as [[United States Air Force Combat Rescue Officer|Combat Rescue Officer]]s\u2014wear a modified version of this metallic beret flash just above their miniature polished metal rank insignia, also on maroon berets centered over their left eye.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"STO and CRO\"/>  It is unclear when the Pararescueman Beret Flash became an official part of the uniform.\n\n{{multiple image\n|header  = Weather Parachutist beret flashes (1960s\u20132010)\n|perrow  = 3\n|width1  = 111\n|image1  = US Air Force 1960s Combat Weather Team beret flash-Unofficial.svg\n|caption1= 1960s unofficial Commando Weatherman Beret Flash\n|width2  = 104\n|image2  = Former US Air Force 5th Weather Squadron Beret Flash.svg\n|caption2= 1970\u20131980s 5th Weather Squadron Beret Flash\n|width3  = 104\n|image3  = Former US Air Force Combat Weather Team Beret Flash.svg\n|caption3= 1979\u201386 & 1992 \u201396 SOWT Beret Flash, 1996\u201310 CWT Beret Flash\n|width4  = 105\n|image4  = 1986-2001 US Air Force SOWT Beret Flash.png\n|caption4= 1986\u201391 SOWT Beret Flash, 1992-96 SOWT Beret Crest, 1996-02 CWT Beret Crest\n|width5  = 102\n|image5  = Former US Air Force Special Operations Weather Technician beret flash-1.svg\n|caption5= 1996\u20132007 AFSOC's SOWT Beret Flash\n|width6  = 114\n|image6  = USAF Special Operations Weatherman Flash.jpg\n|caption6= 2002-2006 SOWT & CWT Beret Crest, 2007\u20132010 SOWT Beret Flash & CWT Beret Crest\n}}\n[[File:USAF SOWT graduation-beret ceremony.jpg|thumb|right|160px|A SOWT wearing the Special Operations Weather Beret Flash, ca. 2017]]\n{{Stack|[[File:USAF Special Operations Weather Team Flash.png|thumb|right|120px|2010\u20132018 Special Operations Weather Beret Flash]]}}\nIn the mid 1960s, [[United States Air Force Special Reconnaissance|US Air Force Commando Weathermen]]<ref name=\"SOWT Overview\">[https://www.afsoc.af.mil/About-Us/Fact-Sheets/Display/Article/494099/special-operations-weather-team/ Special Operations Weather Team], AFSOC, dated\n12 August 2014, last accessed 15 March 2020</ref>\u2014also known as Weather Parachutists\u2014with Detachment 26, [[30th Weather Squadron]] and Detachment 32, 5th Weather Squadron informally wore black berets with a rectangular beret flash.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\">[https://media.defense.gov/2015/Sep/11/2001329838/-1/-1/0/AFD-150911-027.pdf Air Force Weather, Our Heritage 1937 to 2012], prepared by TSgt C. A. Ravenstein (Historical Division, AW3DI, Hq AWS), dated 22 January 2012, last accessed 14 March 2020</ref>  This black beret flash had a depiction of a yellow embroidered [[anemometer]] surmounted by a [[fleur-de-lis]] with the words \u201cCombat Weather\u201d split by the anemometer.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  In 1963, Weather Parachutists from Detachment 75, 2nd Weather Group wore gray berets and like the Pararescueman and Combat Controllers of the era used their Parachutist Badge as their beret flash and worn their polished metal rank insignia (enlisted, NCO, and officer alike) just below their badge.<ref name=\"CSAR 1967\"/><ref name=\"Vietnam CCT\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  From 1970 through the 1980s, Weather Parachutists with the 5th Weather Squadron wore maroon berets with a US Army style beret flash that incorporated [[:File:5 Weather Sq emblem.png|the squadron's colors from their emblem's]] [[alchemical symbol]] for water\u2014the green, blue, and red colors inside the symbol were designed to represent Earth, air, and fire respectively\u2014and wore their Parachutist Badge on top of the flash.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  In 1979, Weather Parachutists\u2014now commonly known as Special Operations Weather Teams (SOWTs)\u2014where authorized to wear dark-blue berets with a US Army style beret flash consisting of a blue and black field surrounded by yellow piping.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  Enlisted and NCOs wore their Parachutist Badge on top of the flash while officers wore their polished metal rank insignia, just as US Army officers do today.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  In July 1986, the gray beret was authorized for wear by all SOWTs who continued to wear the aforementioned cloth beret flash until a new large color metallic SOWT Beret Flash was authorized.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  This large metallic beret flash used the same color field as the previous cloth flash but had a parachute with the letters \"USAF,\" a dagger, and lightning bolts centered in the field with a scroll at the bottom embossed with the words \u201cAir Weather Service;\u201d this metal beret flash was surrounded by a [[Gilding|gilded]] band embossed with the words \u201cSpecial Operations Weather Team.\"<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  In June 1992, the US Air Force approved the return of the SOWT's blue, black, and yellow cloth beret flash from the 70s and used their color metallic SOWT Beret Flash from the 80's as the beret's crest (i.e. it was placed on top of the cloth beret flash).<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  In June 1996, the SOWTs assigned to the US [[Air Force Special Operations Command]] (AFSOC) wore a new US Army style beret flash while those assigned to [[Air Combat Command]] (ACC)\u2014known as Combat Weatherman (CWT)<ref name=\"SOWT CWT\">[https://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/Visit/Museum-Exhibits/Fact-Sheets/Display/Article/195960/special-operations-weather-technicians-and-officers/ Special Operations Weather Technicians and Officers], [[National Museum of the United States Air Force]], dated 2 June 2015, last accessed 16 March 2020</ref>\u2014continued to wear the original blue, black and yellow beret flash.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  AFSOC's SOWT Beret Flash consisted of a red border representing the blood shed by their predecessors, a black background represented special operations, and three colored diagonal lines represented the services they supported (green=US Army, purple=joint forces, and blue=US Air Force).<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  Enlisted and NCOs wore their Parachutist Badge on top of AFSOC's SOWT Beret Flash while officers wore their polished metal rank insignia until 2002 when the Combat Weather Team Crest was created.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/>  The Combat Weather Team Crest incorportated the center elements of the 1986 metallic SOWT Beret Flash/Crest\u2014specifically the parachute, crossed lightning bolts, and dagger\u2014with arched banners embossed with \"Combat Weather Team\" above, \"Airborne\" below, and \"USAF\" in a center rectangular banner.  The Combat Weather Team Crest was worn on top of both SOWT and CWT beret flashes by enlisted and NCOs while officers continued to wear their metal rank insignia.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/><ref name=\"AFSOC SOWT Flash\">[http://www.keesler.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/363549/earning-the-gray-beret/ Earning the gray beret], Keesler Air Force Base public website, dated 10 June 2008, last accessed 18 July 2017</ref><ref name=\"SOWT ACC Flash\">[https://www.flickr.com/photos/rcsadvmedia/5871025429/in/album-72157627591270415/ Christian Shepherd, 18th Weather Squadron Combat Weatherman], flickr.com, dated 7 October 2007, last accessed 18 July 2017</ref>  In 2007/2008, AFSOC's SOWT Beret Flash stopped being worn and the Combat Weather Team Crest became the de facto beret flash for these units.<ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/><ref name=\"2010 SOWT in ceremony\">[https://www.353sog.af.mil/News/Stories/Article/459758/sts-kicks-off-kadenas-remembrance-ceremony/ STS kicks off Kadena\u2019s remembrance ceremony], 353sog.af.mil, by SSgt Christopher Hummel, dated 12 November 2010, last accessed 8 March 2020</ref>  In January 2009\u2014when the Special Operations Weather AFSC was established\u2014a new large metallic Special Operations Weather Beret Flash was approved for wear by all SOWTs and CWTs (enlisted, NCOs, and officers alike) but took an additional year to create and is worn in the same manner as the modern-day CCT and Pararescueman Beret Flashes.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"Weatherman History\"/><ref name=\"2010 SOWT in ceremony\"/><ref name=\"SOWT Graduation\">[https://www.facebook.com/pg/Special-Operations-Weather-Team-Recruiting-156014841107605/photos/?tab=album&album_id=165127260196363 Special Operations Weather Team Recruiting Facebook page], Facebook.com, dated 9 December 2010, last accessed 18 July 2017\u2014Image of the [[:File:USAF Special Operations Weather Beret.jpg|SOWT beret and beret flash from this website is available on Commons]]</ref>  In 2019, SOWTs were re-designated Special Reconnaissance so the name embossed on the Special Operations Weather Beret Flash was changed to \"SPECIAL U.S.A.F. RECON\" and its fleur-de-lis was removed, otherwise this last variant of the Special Operations Weather Beret Flash remains the same.<ref name=\"SR\">[https://www.airforcetimes.com/news/your-air-force/2019/05/13/spec-ops-weathermen-get-name-change-new-mission-to-better-better-fight-great-powers/ Spec ops weathermen get name change, new mission to better fight great powers], AirForceTimes, by Kyle Rempfer, dated 13 May 2019, last accessed 16 September 2019</ref><ref name=\"SR Flash Name Change\">[http://soldiersystems.net/2019/07/03/new-usaf-special-warfare-symbol/ New USAF Special Warfare Symbol], soldiersystems.net, dated 3 July 2019, last accessed 11 December 2019</ref>\n\n[[File:USAF Air Mobility Liaison Officer wearing black beret with unique beret flash.jpg|thumb|175px|An AMLO wearing AMLO Beret Flash with rank insignia on top, prior to TIOH design approval, ca. 2011]]\n{{Stack|[[File:USAF Air Mobility Liaison Officer Beret Flash.svg|thumb|100px|AMLO Beret Flash (a TACP Beret Flash with compass rose)]]}}\nIn 1979, TACP airmen were given authorization to wear the black beret.  In 1984, two TACP airmen submitted a design for a unique beret flash and [[:File:Air Force TACP Badge.jpg|crest]] that would be similar in design and worn in the same manner as US Army beret flashes.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/><ref name=\"Beret History\"/>  The US Air Force approved the TACPs' flash and crest design in 1985.<ref name=\"Beret History\"/>  The TACP Beret Flash incorporates red borders that represent the firepower TACP's bring to bear with two [[Dovetail joint|dovetailed]] fields of blue and green represent the close working relationship between the US Air Force and US Army that is enabled by the TACP.<ref name=\"TACP Flash and Crest Heraldry\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NX-uvMzxQSE TACP - Flash and Crest Heraldry], by ClearedHotProduction, hosted on [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCdJnO93k4mtNQ4a1DXx1Qyg ClearedHotProduction YouTube Channel], dated 20 March 2012, last accessed 31 December 2019</ref>  The TACP Crest incorporates am arched banner at its top embossed with \"U.S. Air Force\" held up by erect\u2013wings\u2014which symbolize the combat readiness of the TACP\u2014at its center is a sword\u2014symbolizes the firepower controlled by the TACP\u2014a lightning bolt\u2014representing modern\u2013day communications used by the TACP\u2014and an eight-point star\u2014symbolizes the worldwide mobility commitment of the TACP; at the base of the erect-wings is a rectangular banner embossed with the letters \"TACP.\"<ref name=\"TACP Flash and Crest Heraldry\"/>  Latter, Air Liaison Officers (ALOs) were given authorization to wear the black beret and the TACP Beret Flash (no crest).<ref name=\"Beret History\"/><ref name=\"274th ASOS Change of Command\">[https://www.174attackwing.ang.af.mil/News/Photos/igphoto/2000249860/ 274th ASOS Change-of-Comand and Ribbon Cutting Ceremonies], 174attackwing.ang.af.mil, by SSgt James N. Faso, dated 4 June 2011, last accessed 8 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"ALO\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180713100539/http://static.e-publishing.af.mil/production/1/af_a3_5/publication/cfetp13lxx/cfetp13lxx.pdf AFSC 13LX Air Liaison Officer, Career Field Education and Training Plan], Department of the Air Force, dated 21 May 2013, last accessed 5 March 2020</ref>  In 2019 US Air Force uniform instruction changed directing ALOs, now called TACP Officers, to where the TACP flash and crest with miniature polished metal rank insignia below the crest and just above the outer-border of the beret flash.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"TACP Officer Selection\">[https://www.airforce.com/api/document/download/1457 TACP Officer Assessment and Selection, Application Process], airforce.com, dated FY2020, last accessed 7 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"ALO Officer\">[https://www.facebook.com/garandthumb1/photos/a.841686645853932/2513113788711201/?type=3&theater \"Garand Thumb,\" a US Air Force Air Liaison Officer and YouTuber, photographed in his service dress uniform], Facebook, public access photo (unrestricted), dated 27 September 2019, last accessed 30 December 2019</ref>  Similarly, Air Mobility Liaison Officers (AMLOs) were also wore the black beret.<ref name=\"Beret History\"/>  Although worn informally before then, in January 2015 TIOH authorized a slight modification of the TACP Beret Flash for wear by AMLOs which incorporated a [[compass rose]] in the upper-left corner of the beret flash and is worn in the same manner as US Army beret flashes.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/><ref name=\"ALMO flash\">[https://www.eaglesofwar.com/Images/1%20Shoulder%20Sleeve%20Insignia/Beret%20Flashes%20and%20Background%20Trimmings/A-4-299%20AIR%20MOBILITY%20LIAISON%20OFFICER.pdf USAF, Air Mobility Liaison Officer, A-4-299], The Institute of Heraldry via the Eagles of War website, dated 20 January 2015, last accessed 14 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"AMLO Wearing Beret\">[https://www.flickr.com/photos/usarmyeurope_images/6205399942 U.S. Army Europe, Clearing the DZ], U.S. Army Europe Flickr page, dated 29 September 2011, last accessed 23 March 2019</ref>  Despite this, US Air Force uniform regulations do not address the wear of the AMLO Beret Flash by these liaisons.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/>\n\nIn 2004, the US Air Force authorized the wear of the pewter-green beret to graduates of the US Air Force [[Survival, Evasion, Resistance and Escape]] (SERE) specialist technical school.  This beret's flash is a polished metal shield embossed with their SERE emblem and motto, \"Return With Honor\" and is worn centered over the left eye.<ref name=\"AFI36-2903\"/><ref name=\"SERE beret\">[http://www.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/135399/sere-graduates-authorized-berets/ SERE graduates authorized berets], US Air Force, by A1C Nathan Putz (92nd Air Refueling Wing Public Affairs), dated 14 December 2004, last accessed 17 June 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2018, AFSOC authorized the wear of the brown beret for airman, NCOs, and officers assigned to CAA squadrons.  The brown beret is worn with a US Army style cloth beret flash consisting of a dark-blue field with olive-green stripes and border.<ref name=\"DA PAM 670-1\"/><ref name=\"CAA Beret\">[http://www.afsoc.af.mil/News/Article-Display/article/1410562/quiet-professionals-don-brown-beret/ Quiet Professionals don brown beret], AFSOC, by Capt Monique Roux (919th Special Operations Wing Public Affairs), dated 8 January 2018, last accessed 5 July 2018</ref>  The cloth beret flash is worn centered over the left eye with officers wearing their medal rank insignia on top of the flash.<ref name=\"CAA Beret\"/>\n\n===US Navy===\n[[File:428-GX-USN 1142474 (26370944616).jpg|thumb|right|265px|[[Chief of Naval Operations]] and COMRIVPATFOR wearing berets with Task Force 116 patch as the beret's flash, ca. 1969]]\n{{Stack|[[File:US Navy TF-116 Patch.png|thumb|right|135px|River Patrol Force, Task Force 116 insignia]]}}\nIn the 1960s, select [[United States Navy|US Navy]] [[Brown-water navy|riverine patrol units]] adopted the black beret to be part of their daily uniform and wore various accouterments on their berets that served as the beret's flash.<ref name=\"Navy Black Beret\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=mlQJrG0EASAC&q=black+beret#v=snippet&q=black%20beret&f=false Brown Water, Black Berets: Coastal and Riverine Warfare in Vietnam], Naval Institute Press, by [[Thomas J. Cutler]], dated 2000, {{ISBN|1557501963}}, last accessed 24 October 2018</ref><ref name=\"Riverine Beret\">[http://www.tf116.org/pdf/Glickman67-68.pdf River Patrol Force/River Patrol Flotilla Five (TF-116), Operation Game Warden, 8 November 1967 - 3 November 1968], by Thomas W. Glickman, dated 14 July 2008, last accessed 24 October 2018</ref>  In April 1967, Commander of the Riverine Patrol Force (COMRIVPATFOR) sent an official message to the Commander of River Patrol Flotilla Five authorizing the wear of the black beret.  In this message, COMRIVPATFOR defined the wear and appearance of the beret along with its distinctive flash stating, \"Beret will be worn with river patrol force insignia centered on right side.\" and \"Only standard size river patrol force insignia will be worn on beret. ... No other emblem or rank insignia will be displayed on beret.\"<ref name=\"Riverine Beret\"/><ref>[https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/our-collections/photography/numerical-list-of-images/nhhc-series/nh-series/NH-69000/NH-69307.html NH 69307 Uniform], Naval History and Heritage Command, last accessed 13 April 2019</ref>  Today, these US Navy small boat units honor their [[Vietnam]] heritage by wearing the black beret with historically relevant riverine task force beret flash during special occasions, such as award and promotion ceremonies.<ref name=\"Navy ceremony-beret\">[https://www.navy.mil/view_image.asp?id=94528 US Navy photo: 101123-N-9095H-009], by Mass Communication Specialist 2nd Class Michael R. Hinchcliffe, dated 23 November 2010, last accessed 24 October 2018</ref><ref name=\"Navy ceremony2-beret\">[https://www.navy.mil/view_image.asp?id=103366 US Navy photo: 110624-N-ZZ999-004], by Intelligence Specialist 2nd Class Scott Solis, dated 24 June 2011, last accessed 12 October 2019</ref><ref name=\"USN Riverine Unit Ceremony\">[https://www.snafu-solomon.com/2014/11/us-navy-riverines-wearing-berets-now.html US Navy Riverines wearing berets now?], SNAFU!, by \"Solomon,\" dated 7 November 2014, last accessed 24 October 2018</ref><ref name=\"Navy ceremoney3-beret\">[https://www.dvidshub.net/image/592144/coastal-riverine-force-establishment Coastal Riverine Force establishment (Image 3 of 4)], DVIDS, by Petty Officer 1st Class Julian Olivari, dated 1 June 2012, last accessed 23 February 2020</ref>\n\n===Female service uniform beret devices===\nStarting in the 1970s, a special female beret was authorized for wear as alternate headgear for the US Army, US Air Force, US Navy, and US Marine Corps with various [[service uniform]]s.<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/><ref name=\"Air Force Female Beret\">[https://www.162wing.ang.af.mil/News/Features/Display/Article/444888/from-the-waf-to-the-guard-a-woman-reflects-on-her-air-force-career/ From the \u2018WAF\u2019 to the Guard, a woman reflects on her Air Force career]; US Air Force; by 2nd Lt. Angela Walz, 162nd Fighter Wing Public Affairs; dated 26 February 2010, last accessed 12 April 2019</ref><ref name=\"Marine Female Beret\">[http://www.usmilitariaforum.com/forums/index.php?/topic/185507-usmc-womens-service-dress-caps/ USMC Women's Service & Dress Caps], US Militaria Forum, started by \"usmc-collector\" on 19 August 2013, last accessed 12 April 2019</ref><ref name=\"Navy Historical Reg\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20070521043303/http://buperscd.technology.navy.mil/bup_updt/508/unireg/chapter3/3500_seriesArticles/3501_3.htm U.S. Navy Uniform Regulations (Historical)], dated January 1998, last accessed 30 August 2019</ref>  The US Navy was the last service to remove the female beret from their uniform regulations in September 2015.<ref name=\"NAVADMIN 208 15\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180916195314/https://www.public.navy.mil/bupers-npc/reference/messages/Documents/NAVADMINS/NAV2015/NAV15208.txt NAVADMIN 208/15], Department of the Navy, dated 1 September 2015, last accessed 30 August 2019</ref>  These black (Army), dark-blue (Air Force), navy-blue (Navy), and dark-green (Marine Corps) female berets were of similar design and worn on the crown of the head.<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/><ref name=\"Air Force Female Beret\"/><ref name=\"Marine Female Beret\"/><ref name=\"Navy Historical Reg\"/><ref name=\"Army Female Beret\">[http://webdoc.sub.gwdg.de/ebook/p/2005/CMH_2/www.army.mil/cmh-pg/books/wac/appendix-d.htm Appendix\u2013D, Women's Army Corps Uniforms 1942\u20131978], University of G\u00f6ttingen, last accessed 12 May 2019</ref>  These service members wore their traditional [[Peaked cap#United States|cap devices]] on these female berets but unlike today's US Army and US Air Force beret flashes, these devices were worn center-forward on the beret.<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/><ref name=\"Air Force Female Beret\"/><ref name=\"Marine Female Beret\"/><ref name=\"Navy Historical Reg\"/><ref name=\"Army Female Beret\"/>\n\nCommissioned officers of the US Army wore a gold metal replica of the [[Great Seal of the United States|coat of arms of the United States]] on their female berets<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/> while US Air Force commissioned officers, commissioned warrant officers, and warrant officers wore a silver version of the same insignia.<ref name=\"USAF Uniform History\">[http://usafflagranks.com/usaf_service_dress_coat_uniform.html Service Dress Coat Uniform,Winter USAF Blue Shade 84, Service Dress 1949\u20131965], USAF FLag Ranks, by: Bro John Schlund, last updated 22 January 2010, last accessed 13 April 2019''\u2014Note: This is the only information found on what US Air Force warrant officers wore as their headgear device and based on US military tradition, it is assumed that this device was also used on the Air Force female service uniform beret.''</ref>  US Army commissioned warrant officers and warrant officers wore a gold metal spread\u2013eagle enclosed within a wreath on their female berets.<ref name=\"Eagle Rising\">[https://warrantofficerhistory.org/Origin_of_Eagle_Rising.htm Origin of the Eagle Rising, Original Distinctive Insignia of the Army Warrant Officer], Warrant Officer Historical Foundation, last updated 1 June 2015, last accessed 21 August 2019</ref>  US Navy commissioned officers and commissioned warrant officers wore a silver spread\u2013eagle surmounting a silver shield and gold fouled anchors on their female berets while warrant officers wore only the gold fouled anchors until commissioned.<ref name=\"Navy Historical Reg-Officer\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20070406111807/http://buperscd.technology.navy.mil/bup_updt/508/unireg/chapter4/chapter_4sec3pt1.htm#chap4311 U.S. Navy Uniform Regulations (Historical), Chapter Four, Rank/Rate Insignia, Section 3: Headgear Insignia, PART 3: El - E6 Headgear Insignia], dated January 1998, last accessed 30 August 2019</ref>\n\nUS Army and US Air Force enlisted and NCOs wore a gold\u2014for the US Army\u2014or silver\u2014for the US Air Force\u2014metal replica of the coat of arms of the United States surrounded by a like-colored metal ring on their female berets.<ref name=\"AR670-1 1981\"/><ref name=\"Air Force Female Beret\"/>  US Navy enlisted and NCOs wore a silver spread\u2013eagle with the letters \"USN\" mounted above the wings on their female berets while [[List of United States Navy enlisted rates#E-7 to E-9|senior NCOs (E-7/OR-7 through E-9/OR-9)]] wore their polished metal rank insignia.<ref name=\"Navy Historical Reg-Enlisted\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20070623130702/http://buperscd.technology.navy.mil/bup_updt/508/unireg/chapter4/chapter_4sec3pt3.htm#chap4331 U.S. Navy Uniform Regulations (Historical), Chapter Four, Rank/Rate Insignia, Section 3: Headgear Insignia, Part 1: Commissioned Officer and Warrant Officer Headgear Insignia], dated January 1998, last accessed 30 August 2019</ref><ref name=\"Navy Historical Reg-Chiefs\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20070606062948/http://buperscd.technology.navy.mil/bup_updt/508/unireg/chapter4/chapter_4sec3pt2.htm#chap4321 U.S. Navy Uniform Regulations (Historical), Chapter Four, Rank/Rate Insignia, Section 3: Headgear Insignia, Part 2: Chief Petty Officer (CPO) Headgear Insignia], dated January 1998, last accessed 30 August 2019</ref>\n\nAll US Marines wore a subdued [[eagle, globe, and anchor]] as their female beret flash.<ref name=\"Marine Female Beret\"/>\n{|align=center\n|{{multiple image\n|header  = US military cap devices used on the former female service uniform berets\n|width1  = 110\n|image1  = US Army Female Cap Devices.png\n|caption1= Army cap devices\n|width2  =105\n|image2  = US Air Force Female Cap Devices.png\n|caption2= Air Force cap devices\n|width3  = 173\n|image3  = US Navy Cap Devices.png\n|caption3= Navy cap devices\n|width4  = 70\n|image4  = US Marine Corps Insignia-Subdued.png\n|caption4= Marine Corps Cap Device (subdued)\n}}\n|[[File:US Air Force veteran Brenda West-1974.jpg|thumb|210px|An airman wearing female service uniform beret with Enlisted Cap Device as the beret's flash, ca. 1974]]\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Some military beret flashes currently authorized==\n===Joint beret flashes===\n<gallery>\nFile:United Nations Peacekeeping Beret Flash.jpg|<center>[[United Nations peacekeeping|United Nations Peacekeepers]]</center>\nFile:Multinational Force and Observers Flash.png|<center>[[Multinational Force and Observers]] (cloth version)</center>\n</gallery>\n\n===US Army===\n<gallery>\nFile:Beret flash of the United States Army.svg|<center>US Army ''(worn when no distinctive organizational flash exists)''</center>\n</gallery>\n\n====[[Military acquisition|Acquisition]] and Test====\n<gallery>\nFile:OTC beret flash.gif|<center>[[United States Army Test and Evaluatio