{"title_page": "International World War Peace Tree", "text_new": "{{one source|date=March 2014}}\nThe '''International World War Peace Tree''' is a [[Tilia|linden tree]] on the southwestern edge of [[Darmstadt, Indiana]], serving as a reminder of [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|Germany's armistice]] with the United States in 1918.\n\n==Description==\nThe tree stands on the northwest corner of St. Joseph Avenue and Orchard Road, surrounded by [[cornfields]]. Its relative isolation from the nearby forests makes it easy to identify. In front of the tree is a wooden sign reading, \"International World War Peace Tree - Nov. 11, 1918\".  The date marks the end of [[World War I]]. The tree is {{convert|40|ft}} tall and is at least {{age|1912|12|31}} years old.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\nThe sign in front of the tree is frequently adorned with small [[American flag]]s, particularly around patriotic holidays such as [[Memorial Day]], [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]], and [[Veterans Day]].<ref name = \"courier\">{{cite news|title = Family still tends to WWI 'peace tree'|url=http://www.courierpress.com/lifestyle/family-still-tends-ww-i-peace-tree |first=Rich |last=Davis |journal = [[Evansville Courier & Press]]|date=May 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe tree has its origins in Germany. It was brought to the United States in 1912 as a [[seedling]] by [[Joseph Freudenburg]], prior to World War I. When the treaty with Germany was signed in 1918, a picnic was held on the property of his sister-in-law Mrs. Wortman, and during the picnic, Freudenburg's tree was transplanted to its current location at the intersection of St. Joseph and Orchard in celebration of the end the war. The planting and dedication of this tree by [[German American]] [[immigrants]] served as a sign of their loyalty to America and also to build local community harmony.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\nFreudenburg mounted a flagpole near the tree, but the flagpole has since been removed, although its cement base remains. The garden of flowers that once adorned the tree has also disappeared.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\nThe tree has been maintained since its arrival in America by the same family:\n*1912 or earlier - 1918: Joseph Freudenburg<ref name=\"courier\" />\n*1918 - ?: Son of Mrs. Wortman (nephew of Joseph Freudenburg)<ref name=\"courier\" />\n*? - 1988: Clarence Wortman, his son<ref name=\"courier\" />\n*1988\u2013present: Charles Skeels, husband of Clarence's daughter Beth.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{coord|38.082985|N|87.59809|W|region:US-IN_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Tilia]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Indiana]]\n[[Category:World War I memorials in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Vanderburgh County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Individual trees in the United States]]\n\n\n{{VanderburghCountyIN-geo-stub}}\n{{Malvaceae-stub}}\n{{WWI-stub}}\n{{tree-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{one source|date=March 2014}}\nThe '''International World War Peace Tree''' is a [[Tilia|linden tree]] on the southwestern edge of [[Darmstadt, Indiana]], serving as a reminder of [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|Germany's armistice]] with the United States in 1918.\n\n==Description==\nThe tree stands on the northwest corner of St. Joseph Avenue and Orchard Road, surrounded by [[cornfields]]. Its relative isolation from the nearby forests makes it easy to identify. In front of the tree is a wooden sign reading, \"International World War Peace Tree - Nov. 11, 1918\".  The date marks the end of [[World War I]]. The tree is {{convert|40|ft}} tall and is at least {{age|1912|12|31}} years old.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\nThe sign in front of the tree is frequently adorned with small [[American flag]]s, particularly around patriotic holidays such as [[Memorial Day]], [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]], and [[Veterans Day]].<ref name = \"courier\">{{cite news|title = Family still tends to WWI 'peace tree'|url=http://www.courierpress.com/lifestyle/family-still-tends-ww-i-peace-tree |first=Rich |last=Davis |journal = [[Evansville Courier & Press]]|date=May 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe tree has its origins in Germany. It was brought to the United States in 1912 as a [[seedling]] by [[Joseph Freudenburg]], prior to World War I. When the treaty with Germany was signed in 1918, a picnic was held on the property of his sister-in-law Mrs. Wortman, and during the picnic, Freudenburg's tree was transplanted to its current location at the intersection of St. Joseph and Orchard in celebration of the end the war. The planting and dedication of this tree by [[German American]] [[immigrants]] served as a sign of their loyalty to America and also to build local community harmony.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\nFreudenburg mounted a flagpole near the tree, but the flagpole has since been removed, although its cement base remains. The garden of flowers that once adorned the tree has also disappeared.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\nThe tree has been maintained since its arrival in America by the same family:\n*1912 or earlier - 1918: Joseph Freudenburg<ref name=\"courier\" />\n*1918 - ?: Son of Mrs. Wortman (nephew of Joseph Freudenburg)<ref name=\"courier\" />\n*? - 1988: Clarence Wortman, his son<ref name=\"courier\" />\n*1988\u2013present: Charles Skeels, husband of Clarence's daughter Beth.<ref name=\"courier\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{coord|38.082985|N|87.59809|W|region:US-IN_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Tilia]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Indiana]]\n[[Category:World War I memorials in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Vanderburgh County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Individual trees in the United States]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Indiana]]\n\n\n{{VanderburghCountyIN-geo-stub}}\n{{Malvaceae-stub}}\n{{WWI-stub}}\n{{tree-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_World_War_Peace_Tree"}
{"title_page": "Dalgona coffee", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Whipped drink made with coffee, sugar and chilled milk}}\n{{Recipe}}\n{{Merge to|Beaten coffee|date=April 2020|discuss=Talk:Beaten coffee#Merger proposal (April 2020)}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Dalgona coffee\n| image            = Dalgona coffee.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = A homemade dalgona\n| country          = South Korea, India<!-- this article is about a South Korean variant of an Indian drink; see [[Beaten coffee]]' --><ref name=\"origins\">{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/korea-dalgona-coffee-india-food-diplomacy-potential/395495/|title=Why S. Korea\u2019s Dalgona coffee trend should remind India of its food-diplomacy potential|publisher=[[ThePrint]]|accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>{{disputed-inline|date=April 2020}}\n| course           = [[Drink]]\n| served           = Hot or cold<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/food/recipes/dalonga_coffee_20606|title=Dalgona coffee||accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n| main_ingredient  = [[coffee]], [[sugar]] and [[milk]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = 197<ref>{{cite web | last =Mathur | first =Neha | title =Whipped Coffee (Dalgona Coffee) | quote=\"Calories 197 kcal\" | url=https://www.whiskaffair.com/dalgona-coffee-recipe/ | accessdate = 1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| other            = \n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbioO7wX1SA ''Pyunstorang'' episode featuring Jung Il-woo presenting whipped coffee (Korean language)]\n}}\n'''Dalgona coffee''' is a beverage made by whipping equal proportions of [[instant coffee]], sugar and hot water until it becomes creamy and then adding it to cold or hot milk. Occasionally, it is topped with coffee powder, cocoa, crumbled biscuits, or honey.<ref name=baes>{{cite news | last = Baes | first =Patricia | title =What is dalgona coffee & why is it on everyone's instagram now? | publisher =[[MSN]] | quote=\"The drink itself has origins from Rajasthan(India) where it is also known as whipped coffee or beaten coffee\" | date = 27 March 2020 | url =https://www.msn.com/en-ph/foodanddrink/foodnews/what-is-dalgona-coffee-and-why-is-it-on-everyones-instagram-now/ar-BB11LDuy?li=BBr8Cnv | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref> It is not possible to make dalgona coffee using ground [[coffee bean]]s; instant coffee creates the dense and foamy topping and the reason for this has much to do with the drying process of the coffee granules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wakacoffee.com/blogs/coffeelifeblog/how-to-make-instant-dalgona-coffee|title=Dalgona Coffee: The Latest Instant Coffee Trend From South Korea|website=Waka Coffee|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDalgona coffee is a home-made version of [[beaten coffee]] popularized on social media during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/food-news/s-koreas-dalgona-coffee-is-the-new-quarantine-fad/articleshow/75106688.cms|title=S Korea\u2019s Dalgona coffee is the new quarantine fad - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The viral trend of sharing recipes and photos of the [[Do it yourself|do-it-yourself (DIY)]] coffee first gained prominence during the [[social distancing]] orders in [[South Korea]], and for that reason it is dubbed the 'quarantine drink' or 'quarantine coffee'.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/dalgona-coffee-recipe|title=Dalgona Coffee Is the Internet\u2019s Favorite, Fluffiest Quarantine Drink. Here\u2019s How to Make It|last=Singer|first=Jenny|website=Glamour|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The coining of the name is credited to the [[South Korea|South Korean]] actor [[Jung Il-woo]], who ordered a whipped coffee at an eatery in [[Macau]] during his appearance on a TV show called ''Stars' Top Recipe at Fun-Staurant'' ({{lang|ko|[[:ko:\uc2e0\uc0c1\ucd9c\uc2dc \ud3b8\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub791|\uc2e0\uc0c1\ucd9c\uc2dc \ud3b8\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub791]]}}). He likened the taste to that of ''[[Honeycomb toffee#Korea|dalgona]]'', a type of Korean [[honeycomb toffee]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbioO7wX1SA|title=400\ubc88\uc744 \uc800\uc5b4 \ub9cc\ub4e0\u2605\uc218\ud0c0 \ub2ec\uace0\ub098 \ucee4\ud53c! \uc77c\uc6b0 \ub208\uc774 \ubc88\uca4d! [\uc2e0\uc0c1\ucd9c\uc2dc \ud3b8\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub791/Stars Top Recipe at Fun-Staurant] 20200103|last=|first=|date=3 January 2020|website=Youtube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Navarra|first=Ruth L.|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/359573/how-to-make-the-south-korean-trend-dalgona-coffee/|title=How to make the South Korean trend Dalgona Coffee|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|quote=\"The trend is credited to actor Jung Il-woo after appearing on the show \u201cPyunstorang.\u201d He went to Macau where he was served with a handmade drink. Jung said it was delicious and reminded him of dalgona candy. He called it Macau Dalgona coffee.\"}}</ref>  \n\nUnder the hashtag #dalgonacoffeechallenge, homemade versions of dalgona coffee began spreading on South Korean [[YouTube]] channels before going viral on [[TikTok]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frishberg|first1=Hannah|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/26/how-to-make-whipped-dalgona-coffee-tiktoks-latest-viral-trend/|title=How to make whipped Dalgona coffee, TikTok\u2019s latest viral trend|date=26 March 2020|work=New York Post|accessdate=30 March 2020|language=en|quote=\"The craze started percolating in late January, according to Google Trends, then gained traction near the end of February when a Korean YouTuber posted a now viral, ASMR-style video of how to make the creamy drink.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/food/articles/dalgona_coffee|title=Dalgona coffee: does the internet\u2019s new favourite drink actually work?|work=BBC Food|accessdate=30 March 2020|language=en|quote=\"That\u2019s why, over the last few days, people have been sharing their attempts (especially on TikTok) at making Dalgona coffee.\"}}</ref> The spike in interest during the quarantine period has been attributed to the calming, [[ASMR|ASMR-like]] effects of watching online DIY videos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/bvgbk8/people-all-over-the-world-are-making-frothy-dalgona-coffee-thanks-to-quarantine|title=People All Over the World Are Making Frothy 'Dalgona' Coffee, Thanks to Quarantine|last=Makalintal|first=Bettina|date=2020-03-20|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/dalgona-coffee-whipped-how-to-make-tiktok-instagram-2020-4|title=Dalgona coffee is the whipped coffee drink that's everywhere on TikTok. |last=Haasch|first=Palmer|date=3 April 2020|website=Insider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Although the beverage was popularized as a home-made version of beaten coffee, it is becoming a staple menu item in many coffee shops in South Korea.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Vreeland|first=Vaughn|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/whipped-coffee-recipe.html|title=How to Make Whipped Coffee|date=2020-04-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe drink is also said to closely resemble the Indian beverage known as ''phenti hui'' coffee (or [[beaten coffee]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/korea-dalgona-coffee-india-food-diplomacy-potential/395495/|title=Why S. Korea\u2019s Dalgona coffee trend should remind India of its food-diplomacy potential|last=Gupta|first=Arunima|date=2020-04-05|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The only difference is that when making ''phenti hui'', milk is poured on top of the whipped mix rather than spooning the whipped mix on top of the milk.  \n\nWhile most dalgona coffee doesn't actually contain ''dalgona'', one South Korean cafe does combine ''dalgona'' with milk tea or coffee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/03/10/2020031000064.html|title=\ub775~ \ud560\ub9cc\ud07c \ub2ec\uc544\uc11c\u2026 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ub450\ud1b5\uc774 \ub0a0\uc544\uac00\ub124|date=2020-03-10|website=news.chosun.com|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Frapp\u00e9 coffee]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coffee-stub}}\n{{Coffee|nocat=1}}\t\n\n[[Category:Coffee drinks]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Whipped drink made with coffee, sugar and chilled milk}}\n{{Recipe}}\n{{Merge to|Beaten coffee|date=April 2020|discuss=Talk:Beaten coffee#Merger proposal (April 2020)}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Dalgona coffee\n| image            = Dalgona coffee.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = A homemade dalgona\n| country          = South Korea, India<!-- this article is about a South Korean variant of an Indian drink; see [[Beaten coffee]]' --><ref name=\"origins\">{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/korea-dalgona-coffee-india-food-diplomacy-potential/395495/|title=Why S. Korea\u2019s Dalgona coffee trend should remind India of its food-diplomacy potential|publisher=[[ThePrint]]|accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>{{disputed-inline|date=April 2020}}\n| course           = [[Drink]]\n| served           = Hot or cold<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/food/recipes/dalonga_coffee_20606|title=Dalgona coffee||accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n| main_ingredient  = [[coffee]], [[sugar]] and [[milk]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = 197<ref>{{cite web | last =Mathur | first =Neha | title =Whipped Coffee (Dalgona Coffee) | quote=\"Calories 197 kcal\" | url=https://www.whiskaffair.com/dalgona-coffee-recipe/ | accessdate = 1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| other            = \n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbioO7wX1SA ''Pyunstorang'' episode featuring Jung Il-woo presenting whipped coffee (Korean language)]\n}}\n'''Dalgona coffee''' is a beverage made by whipping equal proportions of [[instant coffee]], sugar and hot water until it becomes creamy and then adding it to cold or hot milk. Occasionally, it is topped with coffee powder, cocoa, crumbled biscuits, or honey.<ref name=baes>{{cite news | last = Baes | first =Patricia | title =What is dalgona coffee & why is it on everyone's instagram now? | publisher =[[MSN]] | quote=\"The drink itself has origins from Rajasthan(India) where it is also known as whipped coffee or beaten coffee\" | date = 27 March 2020 | url =https://www.msn.com/en-ph/foodanddrink/foodnews/what-is-dalgona-coffee-and-why-is-it-on-everyones-instagram-now/ar-BB11LDuy?li=BBr8Cnv | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref> It is not possible to make dalgona coffee using ground [[coffee bean]]s; instant coffee creates the dense and foamy topping and the reason for this has much to do with the drying process of the coffee granules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wakacoffee.com/blogs/coffeelifeblog/how-to-make-instant-dalgona-coffee|title=Dalgona Coffee: The Latest Instant Coffee Trend From South Korea|website=Waka Coffee|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDalgona coffee is a home-made version of [[beaten coffee]] popularized on social media during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/food-news/s-koreas-dalgona-coffee-is-the-new-quarantine-fad/articleshow/75106688.cms|title=S Korea\u2019s Dalgona coffee is the new quarantine fad - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. The viral trend of sharing recipes and photos of the [[Do it yourself|do-it-yourself (DIY)]] coffee first gained prominence during the [[social distancing]] orders in [[South Korea]], and for that reason it is dubbed the 'quarantine drink' or 'quarantine coffee' <ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/dalgona-coffee-recipe|title=Dalgona Coffee Is the Internet\u2019s Favorite, Fluffiest Quarantine Drink. Here\u2019s How to Make It|last=Singer|first=Jenny|website=Glamour|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>. The coining of the name is credited to the [[South Korea|South Korean]] actor [[Jung Il-woo]], who ordered a whipped coffee at an eatery in [[Macau]] during his appearance on a TV show called ''Stars' Top Recipe at Fun-Staurant'' ({{lang|ko|[[:ko:\uc2e0\uc0c1\ucd9c\uc2dc \ud3b8\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub791|\uc2e0\uc0c1\ucd9c\uc2dc \ud3b8\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub791]]}}). He likened the taste to that of ''[[Honeycomb toffee#Korea|dalgona]]'', a type of Korean [[honeycomb toffee]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbioO7wX1SA|title=400\ubc88\uc744 \uc800\uc5b4 \ub9cc\ub4e0\u2605\uc218\ud0c0 \ub2ec\uace0\ub098 \ucee4\ud53c! \uc77c\uc6b0 \ub208\uc774 \ubc88\uca4d! [\uc2e0\uc0c1\ucd9c\uc2dc \ud3b8\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub791/Stars Top Recipe at Fun-Staurant] 20200103|last=|first=|date=3 January 2020|website=Youtube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Navarra|first=Ruth L.|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/359573/how-to-make-the-south-korean-trend-dalgona-coffee/|title=How to make the South Korean trend Dalgona Coffee|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|quote=\"The trend is credited to actor Jung Il-woo after appearing on the show \u201cPyunstorang.\u201d He went to Macau where he was served with a handmade drink. Jung said it was delicious and reminded him of dalgona candy. He called it Macau Dalgona coffee.\"}}</ref>  \n\nUnder the hashtag #dalgonacoffeechallenge, homemade versions of dalgona coffee began spreading on South Korean [[YouTube]] channels before going viral on [[TikTok]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frishberg|first1=Hannah|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/26/how-to-make-whipped-dalgona-coffee-tiktoks-latest-viral-trend/|title=How to make whipped Dalgona coffee, TikTok\u2019s latest viral trend|date=26 March 2020|work=New York Post|accessdate=30 March 2020|language=en|quote=\"The craze started percolating in late January, according to Google Trends, then gained traction near the end of February when a Korean YouTuber posted a now viral, ASMR-style video of how to make the creamy drink.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/food/articles/dalgona_coffee|title=Dalgona coffee: does the internet\u2019s new favourite drink actually work?|work=BBC Food|accessdate=30 March 2020|language=en|quote=\"That\u2019s why, over the last few days, people have been sharing their attempts (especially on TikTok) at making Dalgona coffee.\"}}</ref> The spike in interest during the quarantine period has been attributed to the calming, [[ASMR|ASMR-like]] effects of watching online DIY videos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/bvgbk8/people-all-over-the-world-are-making-frothy-dalgona-coffee-thanks-to-quarantine|title=People All Over the World Are Making Frothy 'Dalgona' Coffee, Thanks to Quarantine|last=Makalintal|first=Bettina|date=2020-03-20|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/dalgona-coffee-whipped-how-to-make-tiktok-instagram-2020-4|title=Dalgona coffee is the whipped coffee drink that's everywhere on TikTok. |last=Haasch|first=Palmer|date=3 April 2020|website=Insider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Although the beverage was popularized as a home-made version of beaten coffee, it is becoming a staple menu item in many coffee shops in South Korea<ref>{{Cite news|last=Vreeland|first=Vaughn|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/whipped-coffee-recipe.html|title=How to Make Whipped Coffee|date=2020-04-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>.\n\nThe drink is also said to closely resemble the Indian beverage known as ''phenti hui'' coffee (or [[beaten coffee]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/korea-dalgona-coffee-india-food-diplomacy-potential/395495/|title=Why S. Korea\u2019s Dalgona coffee trend should remind India of its food-diplomacy potential|last=Gupta|first=Arunima|date=2020-04-05|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The only difference is that when making ''phenti hui'', milk is poured on top of the whipped mix rather than spooning the whipped mix on top of the milk.  \n\nWhile most dalgona coffee doesn't actually contain ''dalgona'', one South Korean cafe does combine ''dalgona'' with milk tea or coffee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/03/10/2020031000064.html|title=\ub775~ \ud560\ub9cc\ud07c \ub2ec\uc544\uc11c\u2026 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ub450\ud1b5\uc774 \ub0a0\uc544\uac00\ub124|date=2020-03-10|website=news.chosun.com|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Frapp\u00e9 coffee]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coffee-stub}}\n{{Coffee|nocat=1}}\t\n\n[[Category:Coffee drinks]]\n", "name_user": "Opencooper", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:refs come after punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dalgona_coffee"}
{"title_page": "Miss World 1981", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox beauty pageant\n| photo = [[File:MW 1981 - Thames TV.png|250px]]\n| caption = Miss World 1981 Titlecard\n| winner = '''[[Pil\u00edn Le\u00f3n]]''' <br> '''{{flag|Venezuela|1954}}'''\n| date = 12 November 1981\n| presenters = [[Peter Marshall (UK broadcaster)|Peter Marshall]], [[Judith Chalmers]]\n| venue = [[Royal Albert Hall]], London, UK<ref name=\"Ribane 2006\"/> \n| broadcaster = [[Thames Television]]\n| entrants = 67\n| placements = 15\n| returns = [[Chile]], [[El Salvador]], [[Iceland]], [[Suriname]], [[Tahiti]]\n| withdraws = [[Mauritius]], [[Panama]], [[Paraguay]], [[Swaziland]], [[American Virgin Islands]]\n| before = [[Miss World 1980|1980]]\n| next = [[Miss World 1982|1982]]\n}}\n\n'''Miss World 1981''', the 31st edition of the [[Miss World]] pageant, was held on 12 November 1981 at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London, UK.<ref name=\"Ribane 2006\"/><ref name=\"Rome News-Tribune\">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19811113&id=tNsvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mTQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3639,2277690&hl=en | title=New Miss World | newspaper=[[Rome News-Tribune]] | date=November 13, 1981 | accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref> The winner was [[Pil\u00edn Le\u00f3n]] from Venezuela,<ref name=\"Rome News-Tribune\"/><ref name=\"Weeks\"/> the first titleholder from her country since [[Miss World 1955|1955]]. She was crowned by Miss World 1980, [[Kimberley Santos]] of [[Guam]]. Another Venezuelan, [[Irene S\u00e1ez]], had been crowned [[Miss Universe 1981]] in July, making Venezuela one of the very few countries to hold both major international titles ([[Miss Universe]] and [[Miss World]]) in the same year. The titles of Continental Queens of Beauty were awarded for the very first time.\n\n==Results==\n[[File:Miss World 1981 Map.PNG|thumb|250px|Countries and territories which sent delegates and results for Miss World 1981<ref name=\"Ribane 2006\"/><ref name=\"Weeks\"/><ref name=\"W.W. Gaunt & Sons 1987\"/>]]\n\n===Placements===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! Final results\n! Contestant\n|-\n| '''Miss World 1981'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Venezuela|1954}}''' \u2013 '''[[Pil\u00edn Le\u00f3n]]'''<ref name=\"Rome News-Tribune\"/><ref name=\"Weeks\"/> \n|-\n| '''1st runner-up'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Colombia}}''' \u2013 Nini Johanna Soto\n|-\n| '''2nd runner-up'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Jamaica}}''' \u2013 Sandra Cunningham\n|-\n| '''3rd runner-up'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Brazil|1968}}''' \u2013 Maristela Grazzia\n|-\n| '''4th runner-up'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|United Kingdom}}''' \u2013 Michele Donnelly\n|-\n| '''5th runner-up'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Australia}}''' \u2013 [[Melissa Hannan]]\n|-\n| '''6th runner-up'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|United States}}''' \u2013 Lisa Lynn Moss\n|-\n| '''Semi-finalists'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Argentina}}''' \u2013 Ana Natali Schoeder Belmut\n* '''{{flag|Belgium}}''' \u2013 Dominique van Eeckhoudt\n* '''{{flag|Canada}}''' \u2013 Earla Stewart\n* '''{{flag|Ireland}}''' \u2013 Geraldine McGrory\n* '''{{flag|Japan|1947}}''' \u2013 Naomi Kishi\n* '''{{flag|Mexico}}''' \u2013 Doris Pontvianne\n* '''{{flag|Trinidad & Tobago}}''' \u2013 Rachel Thomas\n* '''{{flag|Zimbabwe}}''' \u2013 Juliet Nyathi\n|}\n\n===Continental Queens of Beauty===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! Continental Group\n! Contestant\n|-\n| '''Africa'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Zimbabwe}}''' \u2013 Juliet Nyathi\n|-\n| '''Americas'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Venezuela|1954}}''' \u2013 [[Pil\u00edn Le\u00f3n]]\n|-\n| '''Asia'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Japan|1947}}''' \u2013 Naomi Kishi\n|-\n| '''Europe'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|United Kingdom}}''' \u2013 Michele Donnelly\n|-\n| '''Oceania'''\n|\n* '''{{flag|Australia}}''' \u2013 [[Melissa Hannan]]\n|}\n\n==Contestants==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! colspan=4 | EUROPE\n|- \n! Number || Nation || Contestant || Age\n|-\n| align=center | '''01''' || '''{{flag|Austria}}''' |